with domain:
    st.subheader("Domain")
    st.markdown("<p>The domain name in a URL is an important component that identifies the website and its owner. In phishing attacks, attackers may use domain names that are similar to legitimate websites to trick users into visiting malicious sites and revealing sensitive information.\n\nOne common technique used in phishing attacks is to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites and use domain names that are similar to the legitimate website's domain name. For example, an attacker might use a domain name like \"your-bank-login.com\" instead of the legitimate domain name \"yourbank.com\". This can make the fake login page appear more legitimate and trick users into entering their login credentials or other sensitive information.\n\nAttackers may also use subdomains in domain names to create a false sense of legitimacy. For example, an attacker might create a subdomain like \"login.yourbank.com.maliciousdomain.com\" to make the URL appear to be pointing to the user's bank or another trusted organization. In reality, it is sending the user to the attacker\'s website.\n\nIn summary, the domain name in a URL is an important component that can be used by attackers in phishing attacks to make fake websites appear more legitimate. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate. They should also be aware of domain names that are similar to legitimate websites and be particularly cautious when visiting these sites.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with subdomain:
    st.subheader("Sub Domain")
    st.markdown("<p>Subdomains are a part of the domain name in a URL that comes before the main domain name and are used to organize and categorize different sections of a website. In phishing attacks, attackers may use subdomains in various ways to make fake websites appear more legitimate or to bypass security measures.One common technique used in phishing attacks is to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites and use subdomains that are similar to the legitimate website's subdomains. For example, an attacker might create a subdomain like \"login.yourbank.com\" to make the fake login page appear more legitimate and trick users into entering their login credentials or other sensitive information.\n\nAttackers may also use subdomains in domain names to create a false sense of legitimacy. For example, an attacker might create a subdomain like \"login.yourbank.com.maliciousdomain.com\" to make the URL appear to be pointing to the user's bank or another trusted organization. In reality, it is sending the user to the attacker's website.\n\nIn some cases, attackers may use subdomains to bypass security measures or to target specific groups of users. For example, an attacker might create a subdomain like \"hr.yourcompany.com\" to target employees of a specific company.\n\nIn summary, subdomains are a part of the domain name in a URL that attackers may use in phishing attacks to make fake websites appear more legitimate or to bypass security measures. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate. They should also be aware of subdomains that are similar to legitimate websites and be particularly cautious when visiting these sites.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with tld:
    st.subheader("Top Level Domain")
    st.markdown("<p>The TLD (Top-Level Domain) is the last part of a domain name in a URL, such as \".com\", \".org\", or \".net\". In phishing attacks, attackers may use TLDs in various ways to make fake websites appear more legitimate or to bypass security measures.\n\nOne common technique used in phishing attacks is to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites and use TLDs that are similar to the legitimate website's TLD. For example, an attacker might create a domain name like \"yourbank-login.net\" instead of the legitimate domain name \"yourbank.com\". This can make the fake login page appear more legitimate and trick users into entering their login credentials or other sensitive information.\n\nAttackers may also use TLDs in domain names to create a false sense of legitimacy. For example, an attacker might create a domain name like \"login.yourbank.com.maliciousdomain.net\" to make the URL appear to be pointing to the user's bank or another trusted organization. In reality, it is sending the user to the attacker's website.\n\nIn some cases, attackers may use TLDs to target specific groups of users or to bypass security measures. For example, an attacker might create a domain name with a TLD that is associated with a specific country to target users in that country.\n\nIn summary, the TLD in a URL is an important component that attackers may use in phishing attacks to make fake websites appear more legitimate or to bypass security measures. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate. They should also be aware of TLDs that are similar to legitimate websites and be particularly cautious when visiting these sites.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

