with short:
    st.subheader("Short URLs")
    st.markdown("<p>Short URLs are abbreviated versions of longer URLs that redirect to the full URL. In phishing attacks, attackers may use short URLs to hide the actual destination of the link and trick users into visiting malicious websites.One common technique used in phishing attacks is to create short URLs that mimic legitimate URLs. For example, an attacker might create a short URL using a URL shortener service like bit.ly or goo.gl that points to a fake login page that mimics a legitimate banking website. When a user clicks on the short URL, they are redirected to the fake login page, which can then capture their login credentials or other sensitive information.Attackers may also use short URLs to bypass security measures, such as email filters or web filters that are configured to block specific domain names or URLs. By using a short URL, the attacker can hide the actual destination of the link and make it more difficult for the user or the security system to detect the phishing attempt.In summary, short URLs can be used in phishing attacks to hide the actual destination of the link and trick users into visiting malicious websites. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate. They should also be aware of short URLs and be particularly cautious when clicking on links that use them.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with url_path:
    st.subheader("URL Path length")
    st.markdown("<p>Attackers may use URLs with long or complicated paths in various ways to create a sense of urgency or legitimacy, or to obfuscate the actual destination of the link.\n\nFor example, attackers may use URLs with long or complicated paths to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites, and prompt users to enter their login credentials or other personal information. The length or complexity of the path can make the URL appear more legitimate, and may convince users that the website is secure and trustworthy.\n\nIn some cases, attackers may use long or complicated paths in URLs to obfuscate the actual destination of the link. For example, an attacker might use a URL with a long path that redirects the user to a malicious website or downloads malware onto the user's device.\n\nIn summary, the length of the URL path may not have a direct significance in phishing attacks, but attackers may use URLs with long or complicated paths in various ways to trick users into visiting malicious websites or revealing sensitive information. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with ip:
    st.subheader("IP Address")
    st.markdown("<p>In a URL, an IP address (Internet Protocol address) is a numerical label assigned to each device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication. In phishing attacks, attackers may use IP addresses in URLs to make them appear more legitimate or to bypass some security measures.\n\nOne common technique used in phishing attacks is to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites and use IP addresses instead of domain names in the URL. For example, an attacker might use a URL like http://192.168.1.1/your-bank-login to make the fake login page appear to be hosted on the user's own network. This can make the page appear more legitimate, as the IP address may be associated with a device on the user's network.\n\nAttackers may also use IP addresses in URLs to bypass some security measures, such as web filters or firewalls that are configured to block specific domain names or URLs. By using an IP address, the attacker can bypass these filters and make it more difficult for the user or the security system to detect the phishing attempt.\n\nIn summary, attackers may use IP addresses in URLs in phishing attacks to make fake login pages or other malicious websites appear more legitimate or to bypass security measures. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate. They should also be aware that IP addresses can be used in phishing attacks and should not rely solely on the presence of an IP address in a URL as an indication of a legitimate website.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)
    st.image("images/ip.png")

with cnum:
    st.subheader("Numbers")
    st.markdown("<p>Attackers may use URLs with numbers to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites and prompt users to enter their login credentials or other sensitive information. The URLs may include numbers to make them appear more legitimate, such as by including a specific date or time, or a transaction or order number.\n\nAttackers may also use URLs with numbers in phishing emails, such as by including a phone number to call or a reference number to provide when contacting customer support. These numbers may be used to trick users into revealing sensitive information, such as account numbers or passwords.\n\nIn summary, the count of digits in a URL may not have a direct significance in phishing attacks, but attackers may use URLs with numbers to create a sense of urgency or legitimacy and trick users into disclosing sensitive information. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links, verifying the legitimacy of the website, and avoiding entering sensitive information unless they are certain that the website is legitimate.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with https:
    st.subheader("HTTPS Scheme")
    st.markdown("<p>The \"https\" scheme in a URL refers to the use of an encrypted connection between the user's browser and the website server, which helps to protect the privacy and security of the user's information. In phishing attacks, attackers may use fake \"https\" URLs to create a false sense of security and trick users into entering sensitive information.\n\nOne common technique used in phishing attacks is to create fake login pages that mimic legitimate websites, such as banks or social media sites, and use \"https\" URLs to make the pages appear secure. These fake login pages may include fields for users to enter their login credentials or other personal information, which the attacker can then use for nefarious purposes.\n\nIn some cases, attackers may also use other techniques to make their fake \"https\" URLs appear more legitimate, such as including a padlock icon in the browser's address bar or using a URL that includes a trusted domain name. However, these techniques are not foolproof, and users should always be cautious when entering sensitive information on any website.\n\nIn summary, the \"https\" scheme in a URL is intended to provide a secure and encrypted connection between the user's browser and the website server. However, attackers may use fake \"https\" URLs as part of phishing attacks to trick users into entering sensitive information on fake login pages or other malicious websites. Users should always verify the legitimacy of any website before entering sensitive information, even if the website uses an \"https\" URL.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)


