with char8:
    st.subheader("Character '+'")
    st.markdown("<p>The \"+\" character is used in URLs to encode spaces or to separate words in a query string parameter. In phishing attacks, attackers may use the \"+\" character to create URLs that appear to be legitimate, but are actually designed to trick users into providing sensitive information.\n\nOne common technique used in phishing attacks is to create URLs that include a fake login page. When a user clicks on the link, they are taken to a page that looks like a legitimate login page for a well-known service, such as a bank or social media site. The URL for the fake login page may include encoded spaces in the query string that are used to capture the user's login information. For example, an attacker might create a URL like http://yourbank.com/login.php?username=john+doe&password=123+456. In this URL, the \"+\" character is used to represent a space character in the username and to separate the words in the password. When the user enters their login information on the fake login page, the attacker captures their username and password.\n\nAnother way that the \"+\" character can be used in phishing attacks is by creating URLs that include encoded special characters in the domain name or subdomains. For example, an attacker might create a URL like http://you+rba+nk.com. In this URL, the \"+\" character is used to represent spaces in the domain name. This URL may look like it is pointing to a legitimate website, but in reality, it is pointing to a malicious site.\n\nIn summary, the \"+\" character can be used in phishing attacks to create URLs that appear to be legitimate, but are actually designed to capture sensitive information. Users should always be cautious when clicking on links and should verify the legitimacy of the website before entering any sensitive information.</p>",unsafe_allow_html=True)

with length:
    st.subheader("Length of URL")
    st.markdown('<p>The length of a URL can be a factor in phishing attacks in a few different ways.\n\nFirstly, phishing websites often use long, complex URLs to obscure their true nature. By making the URL difficult to read and understand, attackers hope to trick users into clicking on links that they might otherwise avoid.\n\nConversely, legitimate websites often have shorter, simpler URLs that are easier to read and remember. This means that users may be more likely to trust a website with a short URL and less likely to trust a website with a long, complicated URL.\n\nAdditionally, attackers may use a technique called URL spoofing to make a fake website look like a legitimate one by using a long URL that includes the name of the legitimate website. This can make it more difficult for users to recognize that they are on a fake website and may lead them to enter sensitive information, such as passwords or credit card numbers.\n\nIn summary, the length of a URL can be a factor in phishing attacks because attackers may use long, complex URLs to obscure their true nature, or to make fake websites look more like legitimate ones. Conversely, shorter, simpler URLs may be more associated with legitimate websites and can help users identify and avoid phishing attempts.</p>',unsafe_allow_html=True)
